Analysis Challenge Assignment 3¶

Author: Ming Chen¶

Introduction¶

For the purpose of increasing college graduation rates for underpriveleged populations, I decided to create clusters that can display graduation rates and costs of different colleges and universities (especially for students in low-income families who need financial assistance).

I plan to complete the work in 4 sections:

1.Prepare data (create new arrays for selected variables,merge data, drop null and strange data, and z-score transformation)
2.Reduce dimensions (PCA)
3.Identify clusters (K-means)
4.Explain the clusters

1. Prepare data¶

1.1 Import and select¶

According to the purpose, I selected variables that are related to financial stuff and graduation.

• UNITID (used for marking the institution)
• CURROPER (Currently Operating, used for dropping the institutions that were closed)

• TUITFTE (The net tuition revenue per full-time equivalent student), INEXPFTE (instructional expenditures per full-time student)
• COSTT4_A, COSTT4_P (The average annual cost of attendance for academic year institutions and program-year institutions)
• NPT4_048_PUB, NPT4_048_PRIV, NPT4_048_PROG (Average net price of income $0- $48,000)
• PCTFLOAN (the share of undergraduate students who received federal loans in a given year)
• PCTPELL (the share of undergraduate students who received Pell Grants in a given year)
• C150_4_POOLED, C150_L4_POOLED (completion rates for first-time, full-time students who begin school in the fall semester and complete within 150 percent of the expected time to completion for four-year schools and less-than-four-year schools)
• C200_4_POOLED, C200_L4_POOLED (completion rates for first-time, full-time students who begin school in the fall semester and complete within 200 percent of the expected time to completion for four-year schools and less-than-four-year schools)

# K-means to find the clusters

4. Explain the clusters¶

To explain the clusters, there still two things to be done:

  1. List the loadings of PCs, so that it can display what each PC represents.
  2. Plot the classified scatter with labels that can clearly show the meanings for clusters.

Explain:¶

According to the loadings showed above:

PC1 mainly explains the variables of average tuition fee, average cost, and average net price for low-income families, which can represent the average prices of schools. PC2 mainly explains the variables of completion rate within 150/200 percent of the expected time, which can represent the graduation rates of schools.
PC3 mainly explains the share of students who received federal loans/Pell Grants, which can represent the support for student of schools.

Besides, PC1 also explains a large part of the share of students who received federal loans, it actually makes sense because higher price means higher demends of support. However, PC1 explains little for the share of Pell Grants received, which is an important measure of the access a school provides to low-income students (according to FullDataDocumentation for the dataset). So PC3 is a better component to explain the support for those low-income students.

In conclusion:
High PC1 scores mean high price of schools.
High PC2 scores mean high graduation rates.
While high PC3 scores mean low support for low-income students.

Explain:¶

According to the figures showed above,we can identify 5 clusters from 3 dimensions:

Cluster0(blue): low price, middle support, middle graduation
Cluster1(green): relative high price, low support, low graduation
Cluster2(red): middle price, high support, high graduation
Cluster3(purple): middle price, low support, high graduation
Cluster4(yellow): middle price, high support, low graduation

The results indicate that, to increase college graduation rates for underpriveleged populations, we may better recommend schools of cluster2 and cluster0 to those low-income studets. Cluster2 schools have high graduation rates, and they provide high supports for low-income students in spite of middle price for attending schools. Cluster0 schools have middel graduation rates, but the low price and middle support of the schools are appropriate for low-income students.
